WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.882 --> 00:00:15.147
Good morning.
早上好。

2
00:00:15.147 --> 00:00:16.934
When I was a little boy,
在我小时候

3
00:00:16.934 --> 00:00:20.011
I had an experience that changed my life,
有一个经历改变了我的一生，

4
00:00:20.011 --> 00:00:22.919
and is in fact why I'm here today.
这也是我站在这的原因。

5
00:00:22.919 --> 00:00:24.860
That one moment
在那一刻

6
00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:27.122
profoundly affected how I think about
我对艺术、设计和工程的看法

7
00:00:27.122 --> 00:00:30.343
art, design and engineering.
被深深地改变了。

8
00:00:30.343 --> 00:00:33.100
As background, I was fortunate enough to grow up
关于背景，我很幸运地生长在

9
00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:36.813
in a family of loving and talented artists
位于世界最大城市之一的

10
00:00:36.813 --> 00:00:39.377
in one of the world's great cities.
一个充满爱和有才艺术家的家庭。

11
00:00:39.377 --> 00:00:43.254
My dad, John Ferren, who died when I was 15,
我的父亲，John Ferren, 在我15岁的时候去世了，

12
00:00:43.254 --> 00:00:46.784
was an artist by both passion and profession,
他曾是一个热爱艺术的艺术家，

13
00:00:46.784 --> 00:00:49.044
as is my mom, Rae.
同我母亲Rae一样。

14
00:00:49.044 --> 00:00:50.849
He was one of the New York School
他曾是纽约抽象表现主义画家

15
00:00:50.849 --> 00:00:52.610
abstract expressionists who,
的一员，

16
00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:55.122
together with his contemporaries,
他和他的同龄人一起，

17
00:00:55.122 --> 00:00:58.020
invented American modern art,
创造了美国现代艺术，

18
00:00:58.020 --> 00:01:01.205
and contributed to moving the American zeitgeist
并且为在20世纪把美国的时代思潮

19
00:01:01.205 --> 00:01:05.748
towards modernism in the 20th century.
推向现代主义做出了贡献。

20
00:01:05.748 --> 00:01:08.669
Isn't it remarkable that, after thousands of years
在具象派艺术盛行了几千年以后，

21
00:01:08.669 --> 00:01:12.310
of people doing mostly representational art,
相比之下，

22
00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.343
that modern art, comparatively speaking,
现代艺术就像只存在了15分钟，

23
00:01:14.343 --> 00:01:16.683
is about 15 minutes old,
如今卻非常普及，

24
00:01:16.683 --> 00:01:18.581
yet now pervasive.
这难道不是卓越非凡的吗？

25
00:01:18.581 --> 00:01:20.525
As with many other important innovations,
其它许多重要的创新也是如此，

26
00:01:20.525 --> 00:01:24.145
those radical ideas required no new technology,
那些激进的理念无需任何新技术，

27
00:01:24.145 --> 00:01:27.038
just fresh thinking and a willingness to experiment,
只需要创新的思维和敢于尝试的意愿，

28
00:01:27.038 --> 00:01:31.206
plus resiliency in the face of near-universal criticism
加上能够承受几乎所有人批判与反对

29
00:01:31.206 --> 00:01:32.660
and rejection.
的恢复能力。

30
00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:35.177
In our home, art was everywhere.
在我们家里，艺术无处不在。

31
00:01:35.177 --> 00:01:36.748
It was like oxygen,
它就像氧气，

32
00:01:36.748 --> 00:01:39.910
around us and necessary for life.
环绕着我们，也是我们生命的需要。

33
00:01:39.910 --> 00:01:41.769
As I watched him paint,
我看着父亲绘画的时候，

34
00:01:41.769 --> 00:01:44.076
Dad taught me that art
他教导我说艺术

35
00:01:44.076 --> 00:01:46.285
was not about being decorative,
并不是用来装饰的，

36
00:01:46.285 --> 00:01:49.399
but was a different way of communicating ideas,
而是交流思想的另一种方法，

37
00:01:49.399 --> 00:01:51.436
and in fact one that could bridge the worlds
确切的说，这种方法可以把知识和见解

38
00:01:51.436 --> 00:01:54.364
of knowledge and insight.
这两个世界给联系起来。

39
00:01:54.364 --> 00:01:56.504
Given this rich artistic environment,
在这样一个充满艺术气息的环境里，

40
00:01:56.504 --> 00:01:58.119
you'd assume that I would have been compelled
你会认为我会被迫着

41
00:01:58.119 --> 00:02:00.228
to go into the family business,
去从事家族企业，

42
00:02:00.228 --> 00:02:02.844
but no.
但你错了。

43
00:02:02.844 --> 00:02:04.631
I followed the path of most kids
我像那些生来就是为了

44
00:02:04.631 --> 00:02:05.981
who are genetically programmed
逼家长们发疯的小孩子一样，

45
00:02:05.981 --> 00:02:08.180
to make their parents crazy.
选择了另一条路。

46
00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:10.803
I had no interest in becoming an artist,
我对成为一名艺术家毫无兴趣，

47
00:02:10.803 --> 00:02:12.363
certainly not a painter.
更别谈画家。

48
00:02:12.363 --> 00:02:15.662
What I did love was electronics and machines --
我当时爱的是电器和机械--

49
00:02:15.662 --> 00:02:17.282
taking them apart, building new ones,
把他们拆开，建造新的，

50
00:02:17.282 --> 00:02:19.169
and making them work.
并让它们运作。

51
00:02:19.169 --> 00:02:23.071
Fortunately, my family also had engineers in it,
幸运的是，我的家庭中也有工程师，

52
00:02:23.071 --> 00:02:24.279
and with my parents,
他们和我的父母，

53
00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:26.907
these were my first role models.
都是我最早的榜样。

54
00:02:26.907 --> 00:02:28.264
What they all had in common
他们所有人的共同点

55
00:02:28.264 --> 00:02:30.972
was they worked very, very hard.
就是都非常努力地工作。

56
00:02:30.972 --> 00:02:33.342
My grandpa owned and operated a sheet metal
我的祖父曾在布鲁克林拥有一个

57
00:02:33.342 --> 00:02:36.042
kitchen cabinet factory in Brooklyn.
他自己运作的钣金橱柜厂。

58
00:02:36.042 --> 00:02:39.466
On weekends, we would go together to Cortlandt Street,
在周末的时候，我们会一起去Cortlandt 街,

59
00:02:39.466 --> 00:02:42.141
which was New York City's radio row.
现在已经是纽约城的广播站了。

60
00:02:42.141 --> 00:02:44.944
There we would explore massive piles
在那里我们会探索成堆的

61
00:02:44.944 --> 00:02:46.165
of surplus electronics,
盈余的电子产品，

62
00:02:46.165 --> 00:02:48.467
and for a few bucks bring home treasures
和一些物美价廉的宝贝，

63
00:02:48.467 --> 00:02:49.899
like Norden bombsights
比如诺登投弹瞄准器

64
00:02:49.899 --> 00:02:54.410
and parts from the first IBM tube-based computers.
和IBM最早生产的管座电脑的零件。

65
00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:57.476
I found these objects both useful and fascinating.
我发现这些东西很有用也很吸引人。

66
00:02:57.476 --> 00:03:00.107
I learned about engineering and how things worked,
我认识了工程与一些东西的运作原理，

67
00:03:00.107 --> 00:03:01.567
not at school
不是从学校，

68
00:03:01.567 --> 00:03:03.356
but by taking apart and studying
而是通过拆卸和研究

69
00:03:03.356 --> 00:03:05.833
these fabulously complex devices.
这些极度复杂的装置。

70
00:03:05.833 --> 00:03:08.417
I did this for hours every day,
我每天都要在这上面花上好几个小时，

71
00:03:08.417 --> 00:03:11.715
apparently avoiding electrocution.
显然还要防止自己被电死。

72
00:03:11.715 --> 00:03:13.287
Life was good.
美好的生活。

73
00:03:13.287 --> 00:03:15.608
However, every summer, sadly,
然而令人悲哀的是，每个夏天，

74
00:03:15.608 --> 00:03:17.641
the machines got left behind
那些机器都会被抛下，

75
00:03:17.641 --> 00:03:19.845
while my parents and I traveled overseas
因为我父母会带着我出国

76
00:03:19.845 --> 00:03:23.485
to experience history, art and design.
去体验历史、艺术和设计。

77
00:03:23.485 --> 00:03:25.879
We visited the great museums and historic buildings
我们参观了位于欧洲和中东的

78
00:03:25.879 --> 00:03:27.739
of both Europe and the Middle East,
大博物馆和历史性建筑，

79
00:03:27.739 --> 00:03:29.999
but to encourage my growing interest
但为了激励我对科学和科技

80
00:03:29.999 --> 00:03:31.814
in science and technology,
日益增长的兴趣，

81
00:03:31.814 --> 00:03:34.098
they would simply drop me off in places
他们会简单的把我放到

82
00:03:34.098 --> 00:03:36.538
like the London Science Museum,
像伦敦科学博物馆之类的地方，

83
00:03:36.538 --> 00:03:40.256
where I would wander endlessly for hours by myself
在那里我会花几个小时无止尽的独自游走，

84
00:03:40.256 --> 00:03:44.232
studying the history of science and technology.
学习与科学和科技相关的历史。

85
00:03:44.232 --> 00:03:47.496
Then, when I was about nine years old,
然后，在我差不多九岁的时候，

86
00:03:47.496 --> 00:03:49.364
we went to Rome.
我们到了罗马。

87
00:03:49.364 --> 00:03:51.725
On one particularly hot summer day,
在一个格外炎热的夏天，

88
00:03:51.725 --> 00:03:54.604
we visited a drum-shaped building that from the outside
我们参观了一个外观并不起眼的

89
00:03:54.604 --> 00:03:56.848
was not particularly interesting.
鼓形建筑。

90
00:03:56.848 --> 00:03:59.173
My dad said it was called the Pantheon,
我父亲告诉我它被称为万神殿，

91
00:03:59.173 --> 00:04:01.641
a temple for all of the gods.
一个为诸神而建的神殿。

92
00:04:01.641 --> 00:04:03.915
It didn't look all that special from the outside,
从外面它看起来并不特别，

93
00:04:03.915 --> 00:04:06.354
as I said, but when we walked inside,
就像我之前说的， 但当我们走进去的时候，

94
00:04:06.354 --> 00:04:09.667
I was immediately struck by three things:
我瞬间被三样东西震惊了：

95
00:04:09.667 --> 00:04:12.897
First of all, it was pleasantly cool
首先，室内是令人舒服的凉爽，

96
00:04:12.897 --> 00:04:14.975
despite the oppressive heat outside.
尽管室外闷热。

97
00:04:14.975 --> 00:04:17.689
It was very dark, the only source of light
这里面非常暗，唯一的光线来源

98
00:04:17.689 --> 00:04:20.162
being an big open hole in the roof.
是屋顶的一个大洞。

99
00:04:20.162 --> 00:04:22.395
Dad explained that this wasn't a big open hole,
父亲解释说这不是一个大洞，

100
00:04:22.395 --> 00:04:24.209
but it was called the oculus,
而是被称为眼洞窗，

101
00:04:24.209 --> 00:04:26.585
an eye to the heavens.
天堂的一只眼睛。

102
00:04:26.585 --> 00:04:28.730
And there was something about this place,
还有，这个地方有些东西，

103
00:04:28.730 --> 00:04:31.733
I didn't know why, that just felt special.
我不知道为什么，就是感觉很特别。

104
00:04:31.733 --> 00:04:33.731
As we walked to the center of the room,
当我们走到房间的中央，

105
00:04:33.731 --> 00:04:36.552
I looked up at the heavens through the oculus.
我通过眼洞窗仰望天堂。

106
00:04:36.552 --> 00:04:38.849
This was the first church that I'd been to
这是我到过的第一个

107
00:04:38.849 --> 00:04:41.052
that provided an unrestricted view
为神与人之间提供了

108
00:04:41.052 --> 00:04:44.210
between God and man.
直接视野的教堂。

109
00:04:44.210 --> 00:04:47.640
But I wondered, what about when it rained?
但我当时好奇，如果下雨了怎么办？

110
00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:49.497
Dad may have called this an oculus,
虽然我父亲把它称为眼洞窗，

111
00:04:49.497 --> 00:04:52.584
but it was, in fact, a big hole in the roof.
但它实际上就是房顶的一个大洞。

112
00:04:52.584 --> 00:04:54.413
I looked down and saw floor drains
我低头看到了地面的排水管

113
00:04:54.413 --> 00:04:56.998
had been cut into the stone floor.
是切在地面的石头上的。

114
00:04:56.998 --> 00:04:59.457
As I became more accustomed to the dark,
当我变得更适应于黑暗，

115
00:05:00.146 --> 00:05:01.721
I was able to make out details of the floor
我逐渐能够看清地板与周围墙壁

116
00:05:01.721 --> 00:05:03.451
and the surrounding walls.
上的细节了。

117
00:05:03.451 --> 00:05:06.028
No big deal here, just the same statuary stuff
这儿没什么大不了的，只是一些在罗马

118
00:05:06.028 --> 00:05:07.944
that we'd seen all over Rome.
随处可见的雕像罢了。

119
00:05:07.944 --> 00:05:09.616
In fact, it looked like the Appian Way
实际上，它看上去像亚庇古道，

120
00:05:09.616 --> 00:05:11.812
marble salesman showed up
那个大理石推销员带着他的样本书出现，

121
00:05:11.812 --> 00:05:14.260
with his sample book, showed it to Hadrian,
展示给了哈德良，

122
00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:16.900
and Hadrian said, "We'll take all of it."
然后哈德良说："我们全都要了”的地方。

123
00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:18.606
(Laughter)
（笑声）

124
00:05:18.606 --> 00:05:21.824
But the ceiling was amazing.
但天花板还是很惊艳的。

125
00:05:21.824 --> 00:05:24.660
It looked like a Buckminster Fuller geodesic dome.
它看上去像Buckminster Fuller的一个穹顶建筑。

126
00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:25.969
I'd seen these before,
我曾经见过这些，

127
00:05:25.969 --> 00:05:28.213
and Bucky was friends with my dad.
Bucky也是我父亲的朋友。

128
00:05:28.213 --> 00:05:31.704
It was modern, high-tech, impressive,
它很现代、 高科技的、 令人印象深刻，

129
00:05:31.704 --> 00:05:34.141
a huge 142-foot clear span
142 英尺的巨大净跨距

130
00:05:34.141 --> 00:05:37.384
which, not coincidentally, was exactly its height.
也并非巧合的，刚好是是它自身的高度。

131
00:05:37.384 --> 00:05:38.646
I loved this place.
我爱这个地方。

132
00:05:38.646 --> 00:05:42.065
It was really beautiful and unlike anything I'd ever seen before,
它非常的美丽而且是我前所未见的，

133
00:05:42.065 --> 00:05:45.635
so I asked my dad, "When was this built?"
所以我问我父亲："这是什么时候修建的?"

134
00:05:45.635 --> 00:05:48.767
He said, "About 2,000 years ago."
他说："大约 2000 年前"。

135
00:05:48.767 --> 00:05:51.271
And I said, "No, I mean, the roof."
我说："不，我的意思是，屋顶"。

136
00:05:51.271 --> 00:05:53.230
You see, I assumed that this was a modern roof
是这样，我把它默认为一个现代的屋顶，

137
00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:55.148
that had been put on because the original
把它放在那是因为原来的屋顶

138
00:05:55.148 --> 00:05:58.694
was destroyed in some long-past war.
在很久以前的一场战争中被摧毁了。

139
00:05:58.694 --> 00:06:02.156
He said, "It's the original roof."
他说，"它就是原始的屋顶"。

140
00:06:02.156 --> 00:06:04.634
That moment changed my life,
那一刻，我的一生被改变了，

141
00:06:04.634 --> 00:06:07.283
and I can remember it as if it were yesterday.
而且依然令我记忆犹新。

142
00:06:07.283 --> 00:06:09.878
For the first time, I realized people were smart
这是我第一次意识到人类在2000多年前

143
00:06:09.878 --> 00:06:12.018
2,000 years ago. (Laughter)
就很聪明了。（笑声）

144
00:06:12.018 --> 00:06:14.132
This had never crossed my mind.
这点我以前从未想到。

145
00:06:14.132 --> 00:06:18.003
I mean, to me, the pyramids at Giza,
我是说，在我看来，吉萨的金字塔，

146
00:06:18.003 --> 00:06:19.931
we visited those the year before,
我们去年参观过，

147
00:06:19.931 --> 00:06:22.851
and sure they're impressive, nice enough design,
它们确实令人印象深刻、很好的设计，

148
00:06:22.851 --> 00:06:25.306
but look, give me an unlimited budget,
不过，给我无限的预算、

149
00:06:25.306 --> 00:06:29.303
20,000 to 40,000 laborers, and about 10 to 20 years
两万到四万个工人和大概10 至20 年

150
00:06:29.303 --> 00:06:32.919
to cut and drag stone blocks  across the countryside,
在乡村里切割和拖动石头块，

151
00:06:32.919 --> 00:06:35.683
and I'll build you pyramids too.
我也能给你修出金字塔。

152
00:06:35.683 --> 00:06:38.486
But no amount of brute force
但是再多的蛮力也无法

153
00:06:38.486 --> 00:06:41.528
gets you the dome of the Pantheon,
创造出万神殿的圆顶，

154
00:06:41.528 --> 00:06:44.547
not 2,000 years ago, nor today.
两千年前不行，现在也不行。

155
00:06:44.547 --> 00:06:47.287
And incidentally, it is still the largest
顺便说一下，它到目前为止仍是

156
00:06:47.287 --> 00:06:51.101
unreinforced concrete dome that's ever been built.
历史上最大的未加固的混凝土圆顶。

157
00:06:51.101 --> 00:06:54.096
To build the Pantheon took some miracles.
万神殿的修建包含了一些奇迹。

158
00:06:54.096 --> 00:06:56.528
By miracles, I mean things that are
我所说的奇迹是指

159
00:06:56.528 --> 00:06:59.115
technically barely possible,
技术上几乎不可能的、

160
00:06:59.115 --> 00:07:02.187
very high-risk, and might not be
极度高的风险、并且可能

161
00:07:02.187 --> 00:07:04.771
actually accomplishable at this moment in time,
在这一时间段根本无法完成的，

162
00:07:04.771 --> 00:07:09.023
certainly not by you.
当然更不是由你。

163
00:07:09.023 --> 00:07:12.148
For example, here are some of the Pantheon's miracles.
例如，下面是万神殿的一些奇迹。

164
00:07:12.148 --> 00:07:14.841
To make it even structurally possible,
仅仅要让它的结构可行，

165
00:07:14.841 --> 00:07:17.408
they had to invent super-strong concrete,
他们不得不创造超强的混凝土，

166
00:07:17.408 --> 00:07:19.357
and to control weight,
还得控制重量，

167
00:07:19.357 --> 00:07:21.425
varied the density of the aggregate
这是通过在搭建圆顶的过程中

168
00:07:21.425 --> 00:07:24.193
as they worked their way up the dome.
不断改变混合物的密度而达到的。

169
00:07:24.193 --> 00:07:26.494
For strength and lightness, the dome structure
对于强度和轻度，圆顶的结构

170
00:07:26.494 --> 00:07:28.531
used five rings of coffers,
使用了花格镶板的五个圆环，

